## Summary

Implement graceful error handling for CLI unavailability scenarios. When the OpenBrain CLI binary is not found, not executable, or returns errors, the bot must provide a single, clear user-facing error message.

## Background

The CLI may not be present on PATH in all deployments. The current implementation has fallback behavior but needs to be standardized to provide a single, helpful error message explaining CLI unavailability.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Check CLI availability before attempting operations (use `isCliAvailable()`)
- [ ] Provide single, clear error message when CLI is unavailable:
  - "⚠️ OpenBrain CLI is not available. Please ensure the CLI is installed and accessible on PATH."
- [ ] Handle specific error cases:
  - CLI binary not found (ENOENT)
  - CLI binary not executable (EACCES)
  - CLI returns non-zero exit code
  - CLI times out during execution
- [ ] Error message should be consistent across all commands (add, queue, stats)
- [ ] Log detailed error information for debugging (different from user-facing message)
- [ ] Bot must remain operational after CLI errors (no crashes)
- [ ] URLs should still be wrapped in backticks in error responses
- [ ] Build passes (`npm run build`)
- [ ] All tests pass (`npm test`)

## Implementation Notes

### Error Handling Pattern
```typescript
const isAvailable = await isCliAvailable();
if (!isAvailable) {
  await message.reply("⚠️ OpenBrain CLI is not available. Please ensure the CLI is installed and accessible on PATH.");
  return;
}

try {
  for await (const event of runAddCommand(url, context)) {
    // Handle progress
  }
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof CliRunnerError) {
    logger.error("CLI error", { exitCode: error.exitCode, stderr: error.stderr });
    await message.reply(`⚠️ OpenBrain CLI is not available. Please ensure the CLI is installed and accessible on PATH.`);
  }
}
```

### User-Facing vs Debug Messages
- User-facing: Single, clear message about CLI unavailability
- Debug logs: Full error details including exit codes, stderr, stack traces

